# cs-base — Cursor project context

This repo is an Eleventy + Nunjucks + Decap CMS + SASS starter for client web projects. When planning pages, client work, or agency workflow, read the project docs in `docs/` before guessing.

## Project documentation (read when relevant)

### Page layouts — `docs/PAGE-STRUCTURES.md`

Default section order for base and optional pages (Home, About, Services, Contact, etc.). Use this when:

- Adding or restructuring pages
- Choosing which sections/components belong on a page
- Scoping a new client site build

### Freelance agency guide — `docs/FREELANCE-WEB-DEV-GUIDE.md`

Reference for running a freelance web agency: LLC, invoicing, pricing ($150/mo subscription vs lump sum), templates, team, contracts, sales, build checklist, Netlify deploy. Use this when:

- Discussing pricing, contracts, or client onboarding
- Sales scripts, lead qualification, or project management flow
- Pre-launch checklist, hosting, domains (Porkbun), or Netlify setup

### Web design resources — `docs/WEB-DESIGN-RESOURCES.md`

Tools directory, font pair guide (10 pairings by industry), and Page Speed Handbook (`<picture>`, WEBP, local fonts, critical CSS). Use this when:

- Optimizing images, fonts, or Core Web Vitals / Lighthouse scores
- Picking font pairings or linking to external tools (Figma, Pexels, validators, etc.)
- Running the pre-launch performance checklist

## Defaults for implementation

- Match existing kit patterns in `src/` (SASS, Nunjucks, section IDs, `.cs-*` classes).
- Global CSS variables live in `src/assets/sass/root.scss` (`:root`).
- Prefer reusing interior page templates; invest uniqueness in the home page per `docs/FREELANCE-WEB-DEV-GUIDE.md` and `docs/PAGE-STRUCTURES.md`.
- Follow image/font/performance patterns in `docs/WEB-DESIGN-RESOURCES.md` (local fonts via gwfh, `<picture>` + WEBP, no Google Fonts CDN).

## Starting a new client project

When a user says they are starting a new project, starting a new client site, or creating a new site, follow these steps in order. Do not skip steps or assume they are already done.

### Step 1 — Repo setup (user does this manually)
Remind the user to:
1. Go to `cs-base` on GitHub and click **Use this template** → **Create a new repository**
2. Name it after the client (e.g. `smiths-plumbing`)
3. Clone it locally and open in Cursor
4. Run `npm install`

### Step 2 — Fill out client data
Update `src/_data/client.js` with:
- Business name
- Tagline
- Email
- Phone
- Address
- City, state
- Domain (once known)
- Social links (if any)

### Step 3 — Update root variables
Open `src/assets/sass/root.scss` and update the "Update these per client" block:
- `--primary` — client's primary brand color
- `--primaryLight` / `--secondary` / `--secondaryLight` — complementary tones
- `--headerFont` / `--bodyFont` — client's chosen fonts (download and host locally via gwfh.mranftl.com/fonts first)

### Step 4 — Download and add fonts
1. Go to https://gwfh.mranftl.com/fonts
2. Select Latin subset only
3. Download regular, 700, and 900 weights only
4. Place font files in `src/assets/fonts/`
5. Add `@font-face` blocks to `root.scss` with `font-display: swap`
6. Add font preload links to the `<head>` in `src/_includes/layouts/base.html`

### Step 5 — Scaffold pages
Run the following based on what the client needs:

**Base pages (always):**
```bash
npm run create-page -- "About, Services, Contact, Privacy Policy, Terms of Service, Thank You"
```

**Optional drop-ins (add only if client needs them):**
```bash
npm run create-page -- "FAQ"
npm run create-page -- "Gallery"
npm run create-page -- "Testimonials"
npm run create-page -- "Meet the Team"
npm run create-page -- "Areas Served"
```

Also create `src/404.html` manually — it does not use the standard page template.

### Step 6 — Add CMS/blog (only if client is paying for it)
Run:
```bash
# This step is skipped by default — Decap was removed in cs-base
# To add it back, manually re-integrate Decap CMS per the kit documentation
```

### Step 7 — Build the home page
Refer to `docs/PAGE-STRUCTURES.md` for the default home page section order:
1. Hero
2. Social Proof Bar
3. Services Overview
4. Why Choose Us
5. Process / How It Works
6. Testimonials
7. CTA
8. FAQ Snippet

Pick CodeStitch components for each section. Save chosen stitches to a client folder in the CodeStitch library.

### Step 8 — Pre-launch checklist
Before going live, run through every item in `docs/WEB-DESIGN-RESOURCES.md` under **Quick Reference Checklist**. Key items:
- All images use `<picture>` with mobile + desktop WEBP sources
- Fonts hosted locally, preloaded, `font-display: swap` set
- HTML validated, links checked, Lighthouse 100 across all categories
- Sitemap generated, favicon added, schema markup added
- Submitted to Google Search Console
- Netlify form notifications set up for client email + your email
- DNS records moved to Netlify before switching nameservers
